‚ÄúPretty much everybody is convinced that Piazza Duomo has always been the center of Milan. Well, pretty much everybody is completely wrong! Think about it: Piazza Duomo was built only after the Italian Unification in 1861 ‚Ä¶ the true original center of Milan, Mediolanum, is here‚Äù. This is what we have been told by a touristic guide we met in Corso Magenta. As a matter of fact, we are in the area where the Romans, as early as 222 BC, began to lay the stones used to build roads, towers and buildings of what was, until 402 AD, the capital of the Roman Empire.

In 379 A.D. the poet Asuonio, a contemporary of St. Ambrogio, wrote: ‚ÄúIn Milan, everything is wonderful. There is plenty of everything, countless palaces, great minds and people laughing happily‚Äù. Unfortunately, much of this beauty and of the traces left by the Romans were destroyed by the construction of the modern metropolis that has developed right above the old one. In prestigious Caccia Dominioni building, modern spacious and sunny fifth floor flat to rent. Entrance, big living room, one bedroom, big bathroom with bath-tube, kitchen with balcony. Well connected with buses (60 to Railway Station Centrale and 54 to Duomo) and metro (red-line), less than five minutes walking to bikemi station (the rental bike service of Milan).
Situated in a residential area yet providing plenty of opportunities for off-the beaten track shopping and dinining.

Fluent in English, French and  Spanish I love to get to know my hosts and do my best to share tips about the hidden secrets of Milan and Italy in general.
 At home I love to relax, listen to music and of course cooking and wine (after all I am Italian! ).

It's where I lived for 20 years, where I come back when Milan calls.

neighborhood_overview:
Until a few years ago, this was a very popular neighborhood, inhabited mainly by immigrants and disdained by Milanese.
Recently it has become one of the coolest areas in the city, so much so that it also deserves a name that is now a brand: NoLo (North of Loreto).

It's nice to live in NoLo because it's a lively neighborhood, because it has a park in its heart, because it's walking and cycling, because it's multi-ethnic. It's never deserted. Shops and bars are always open and there are many very active neighborhood associations.

Recently, new bars and restaurants have been created for every taste and pocket, and many young artists, architects and creatives are opening activities in the area.
NoLo has also become the new pole not to be missed during the itineraries of the Fuori Salone

For me Airbnb is a way to meet and get in touch with new people.
I love hosting and meeting new people. I want my guests to enjoy something special of Milan and have a 5 stars Airbnb experience. 
Based on my travelling experience (both for work and pleasure) I defined the 6 MUSTs of my apts:
1)  they must express something of the TRUE MILAN: each apt has something which, as a  tourist in my first years in Milan, I loved (the fantastic view which is very difficult to find in Milan, the old courts, ...)
2) they must be a place where I WOULD LOVE TO LIVE (the studio with Duomo view is in the same building where I live with my family, of course in a separate apt!)
3) they must be CENTRAL: walking distance to most attractions, close to bars/restaurants/aperitivos, close to connections to airports and stations
4) they must be CLEAN: when I travel (as a tourist) the cleaning is the first requirement I have!
5) they must be AFFORDABLE for most tourists, without any unexpected expenses and with all comforts (airconditioning, towels, linen, hair dryer, washing machine, iron, ... and of course free WIFI!!!)
6) they must be in a SAFE area: Milan is not a very dangerous town, but, being father of 3 kids, I have chosen the location in an area where I am expecting my sons can walk alone in the evening.

description: Two-room apartment 50 meters away from the Yellow Metro (M3) located in Brenta.
neighborhood_overview:
Located on the south-eastern of Milan, the Brenta district is a complex and composite area, made up of areas that are profoundly different from each other. On the one hand the city that extends from the former Porta Romana railway station towards Piazza Gabrio Rosa, until it reaches the borders of Porto di Mare, on the other the old village that opens up from the Vettabbia Park towards the Chiaravalle countryside.
Following the redevelopment of the area north of the district (now the headquarters of the Prada Foundation), various projects and initiatives have in fact followed one another: from the reopening of the farmhouses in the peri-urban area to the creation of new social spaces for citizens, created to give a new centrality to the neighborhood and its social and cultural richness, history and vocations.

neighborhood_overview: Isola is a trendy neighborhood characterized by graffiti and narrow streets full of trendy boutiques, organic groceries and second-hand shops. Alongside the cozy family-run trattorias are hip cafes set in leafy courtyards, while the casual bars in the area's former warehouses are popular with bikers, punks and students. At the weekend, flea markets are held around the Renaissance church of Santa Maria alla Fontana, known for its frescoed arcades.

name: Charming apartment in a vibrant neighborhood
description: In occasion of the Design Week in April, I am making available the bright and welcoming apartment where I normally live with my family. We are located in Porta Venezia, just outside the inner city walls to the east, one of the liveliest neighborhoods in the city. We are on the third floor, with a beautiful view of a spacious square. Unfortunately, as there is no elevator, the apartment is not accessible to individuals with mobility disabilities.
neighborhood_overview: Porta Venezia epitomizes the multifaceted nature of the city, embracing its cosmopolitan ambiance through a myriad of international cuisines. Celebrating diversity and inclusion, the district hosts LGBTQ+ clubs and is the proud venue for Italy's largest Pride event. It is also a hub for shopping and fashion, boasting stylish boutiques on Corso Venezia that showcase both renowned brands and emerging designer ateliers. The renowned Corso Buenos Aires adds to the allure with its array of window displays. Porta Venezia further reveals its artistic side through the captivating floral architecture of early 19th-century Art Nouveau. Lastly, its natural side unfolds in the English-style gardens, groves, and streams of the Giardini Montanelli.
host_about: I'm an architect, live in Milan with my son, who is 16 years old. I love to travel, play music and sing :-)

enjoy a stylish experience in this centrally-located apartment a few step from the center.
The perfect place to relax and enjoy the typical classy neighborhood with restaurants and cafes and boutiques.
Experience an apartment with character and design furnitures.
neighborhood_overview:
Living in the Arco della Pace area means living in a dynamic context, full of restaurants, nightclubs, shops and much more.
The proximity to Parco Sempione makes this area even more interesting, because it is perfect for those who do not want to leave the center but at the same time also for those who are not willing to give up a green area a few steps from the centre.

Very close is Chinatown, a multi-ethnic neighborhood located around the pedestrian street Paolo Sarpi. The streets are decorated with Chinese lanterns, characteristic colors, the scents of oriental spices, posters and ideogram signs. A place that is definitely worth a visit, if you want to immerse yourself at least for a while in an alternative¬†Milan¬†among ravioli, ramen, bubble tea and small shops.
There are many dining options available, from restaurants serving dim sum, to tea houses and stalls offering Asian snacks.
